[CLAUDE] type: system
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 14
[CLAUDE] tags: [monitoring, observability, alerting, logging]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Monitoring & Observability
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The app has a built-in observability stack that captures request telemetry, application logs, errors, and performance metrics without external APM dependencies.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Components
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Request Observability (`withRequestObservability`)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Every API route handler is wrapped with `withRequestObservability(method, handler)`. This middleware:
[CLAUDE] - Records request start/end timestamps
[CLAUDE] - Captures HTTP method, path, status code
[CLAUDE] - Logs errors with context
[CLAUDE] - Writes to the operational log
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Operational Log
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Structured log entries stored in the `operational_logs` table with severity levels:
[CLAUDE] `debug` | `info` | `warn` | `error` | `critical`
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Also written to `log/observability.ndjson` via `ObservabilityFileSink` for external log ingestion.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Error Fingerprinting
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `src/lib/monitoring/error-fingerprint.ts` — normalizes stack traces and error messages into a stable fingerprint for grouping repeated errors. Enables:
[CLAUDE] - Deduplication of similar errors
[CLAUDE] - Trend tracking over time
[CLAUDE] - Linking error groups to bug records
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Grouped Errors
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `GroupedErrorsService` aggregates error log entries by fingerprint, providing:
[CLAUDE] - Occurrence count
[CLAUDE] - First/last seen timestamps
[CLAUDE] - Sample stack trace
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Accessible via admin API: `GET /api/admin/errors`
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Operational Alerts
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Higher-level alerts derived from error patterns. States: `open` → `acknowledged` → `resolved`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Alerts can be linked to bugs via `POST /api/admin/alerts/[alertId]/bugs`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Performance Metrics
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `EndpointPerformanceService` tracks response time percentiles per API endpoint over configurable time windows. Available at `GET /api/admin/performance/endpoints`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Page Load Observability
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Client-side performance metrics are posted to `POST /api/observability/page-load` and stored for admin review.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Org Usage Stats
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `OrgUsageService` tracks per-organization API usage. Available at `GET /api/admin/performance/org-usage`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Redaction
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `ObservabilityRedaction` (`src/lib/monitoring/observability-redaction.ts`) strips sensitive fields (passwords, tokens, auth headers) before logs are persisted.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Admin Dashboard
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Summary of key system health metrics: `GET /api/admin/dashboard/summary`
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] UI: `/admin/monitoring` and `/admin/dashboard`
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/systems/bug_tracker/agent-integration.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: system
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 8
[CLAUDE] tags: [agent, mcp, automation, api]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Agent & MCP Integration
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The bug tracker exposes two surfaces for automated agent operations.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Agent REST API (`/api/agent/*`)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] A lightweight REST API authenticated via agent API key (not session cookies). Used by automated agents to work bugs in the tracker.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Workflow
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] 1. **Discover** claimable bugs: `GET /api/agent/bugs`
[CLAUDE] 2. **Claim** a bug: `POST /api/agent/bugs/[bugId]/claim` with `{ claimedBy: "agent-name" }`
[CLAUDE] 3. **Work** the bug: agent performs investigation
[CLAUDE] 4. **Update status**: `PATCH /api/agent/bugs/[bugId]/status` with `{ claimedBy, state, statusNote }`
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Agent States
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The `agent_state` field on bugs tracks the agent workflow state (e.g. `claimed`, `investigating`, `done`).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Auth
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Agent requests authenticate using the API key configured in organization settings (`/settings/integrations`). The key is passed in the `Authorization: Bearer` header.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## MCP Server
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `src/lib/bugs/mcp-server.ts` implements a [Model Context Protocol](https://modelcontextprotocol.io) server exposing bug tracker operations as MCP tools for LLM-based agents (e.g. Claude).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Start with:
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] npm run mcp:server
[CLAUDE] # or directly: tsx scripts/mcp-server.ts
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The MCP server lets an LLM agent:
[CLAUDE] - List and search bugs
[CLAUDE] - Read bug details
[CLAUDE] - Update bug status and fields
[CLAUDE] - Add comments
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## CLI Agent Tool
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `npm run bugs:cli` (`scripts/bug-agent-cli.ts`) is a command-line interface that drives the agent REST API. Used for testing and scripted workflows.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Backed by `src/lib/bugs/agent-cli.ts` and `src/lib/bugs/agent-api.ts`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Multi-Agent Coordination
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Per product notes, agents should coordinate when multiple agents work on the same bug set. The `claimed_by` field on bugs provides basic mutual exclusion — an agent should only work bugs it has claimed.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Testing Sessions
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `TestingSessionService` tracks QA agent sessions. During a session, evidence (screenshots, recordings) can be attached to bugs via `POST /api/extension/bugs/[bugId]/evidence`. Session logs are stored in `testing_session_logs`.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/concepts/bug_tracker-domain-model.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: concept
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 10
[CLAUDE] tags: [domain, bugs, organizations, projects]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Bug Tracker — Domain Model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Core Entities
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Organization
[CLAUDE] The top-level tenant boundary. Every user, project, and bug belongs to an organization. Created during signup. Users can belong to multiple organizations and switch between them via the organization switcher.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### User
[CLAUDE] Has a name, email, and password. Can be:
[CLAUDE] - **Regular member** — participates in one or more organizations
[CLAUDE] - **Admin** — full access to admin panel, all organizations
[CLAUDE] - **QA user** — created by admins for testing purposes; can be deactivated
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Project
[CLAUDE] Scoped to an organization. Organizes bugs into logical groupings (e.g. by product area). Projects have a short `key` used for display. Projects can be archived.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Section
[CLAUDE] An ordered sub-grouping within a project (e.g. sprint, milestone, or feature area). Bugs are assigned to a project and optionally to a section.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Bug
[CLAUDE] The central entity. A bug belongs to an organization, project, and optionally a section.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Status lifecycle:**
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] New → Triaged → In Progress → Ready for QA → Closed
[CLAUDE]                                             ↓
[CLAUDE]                                          (Reopened)
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Severity levels** (from badge component):
[CLAUDE] - Low
[CLAUDE] - Medium  
[CLAUDE] - High
[CLAUDE] - Critical
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Key fields:**
[CLAUDE] - `title` — short description
[CLAUDE] - `description` — full detail
[CLAUDE] - `severity` — impact level
[CLAUDE] - `status` — workflow state
[CLAUDE] - `reporter_user_id` — who reported it
[CLAUDE] - `assignee_user_id` — who is working it (nullable)
[CLAUDE] - `is_archived` — soft-delete flag
[CLAUDE] - `agent_state` / `claimed_by` — agent automation fields
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Bug Comment
[CLAUDE] Text attached to a bug. Has a `visibility` field: `internal` (team-only) or `external` (customer-facing).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Bug Attachment
[CLAUDE] A file uploaded against a bug (screenshot, log file, recording).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Bug History
[CLAUDE] Immutable audit trail. Every field change on a bug records a history entry with:
[CLAUDE] - `event_type` — e.g. `bug_created`, `bug_status_changed`, `bug_import_created`
[CLAUDE] - `changed_fields` — array of `{field, previousValue, nextValue}`
[CLAUDE] - Source: either a user action or a system/import action
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Filter Model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The bug list supports filtering by:
[CLAUDE] - Project
[CLAUDE] - Status
[CLAUDE] - Reporter user
[CLAUDE] - Date range (start/end)
[CLAUDE] - Show archived (boolean)
[CLAUDE] - Sort field: `createdAt` | `updatedAt` | `status` | `project`
[CLAUDE] - Sort direction: `asc` | `desc`
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Organization Access Model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Users must be members of an organization to access its data.
[CLAUDE] - The active organization is tracked in the session (`active-organization-session.ts`).
[CLAUDE] - Organization admins have elevated permissions (e.g. view bug history).
[CLAUDE] - Project access can be further restricted (`project-access-context.ts`).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Bug Data Import/Export
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Bugs can be bulk-imported from CSV and exported to ZIP archives.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Import:** validates rows, reports invalid rows with field-level issues, then executes with a configurable duplicate strategy (`skip_existing` | `update_existing`).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Export:** produces a manifest with counts of bugs, history entries, attachments, and missing files.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Jobs are tracked in `bug_data_jobs` with statuses: `queued` → `running` → `completed` / `completed_with_warnings` / `failed`.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/concepts/bug_tracker-auth-model.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: concept
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 8
[CLAUDE] tags: [auth, session, api-keys, jwt]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Authentication Model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The bug tracker supports three authentication methods for different consumers.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## 1. Session-Based Auth (Browser App)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Used by the main web UI.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - **Login**: `POST /api/auth/login` — validates credentials, creates a session record, returns a session cookie
[CLAUDE] - **Session cookie**: name from `getSessionCookieName()`, contains a signed token
[CLAUDE] - **Expiry**: `getSessionMaxAgeSeconds()` / `getSessionExpirationDate()`
[CLAUDE] - **Logout**: `POST /api/auth/logout` — deletes session record and clears cookie
[CLAUDE] - **Guard**: `requireAuthenticatedUser(request)` — used in all protected API routes
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## 2. Extension Token Auth (Chrome Extension)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Uses `Authorization: Bearer <token>` header instead of cookies. The extension obtains a token via `POST /api/extension/auth/login` using the same credentials.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Guard: `requireExtensionAuthenticatedUser(request)` / `getAuthenticatedSessionFromExtensionRequest(request)`
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## 3. Agent API Key Auth
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Used by automated agents hitting `/api/agent/*`. API keys are organization-scoped and managed in settings.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Guard: `requireAgentApiUser(request)` in agent routes.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Email Verification Flow
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] 1. Signup → verification email sent with token
[CLAUDE] 2. User clicks link → `POST /api/auth/verify-email` with token
[CLAUDE] 3. Account marked verified
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Password Reset Flow
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] 1. `POST /api/auth/forgot-password` with email → sends reset email
[CLAUDE] 2. User clicks link with token → `POST /api/auth/reset-password` with `{token, password}`
[CLAUDE] 3. `AuthActionTokenStore` validates and consumes the one-time token
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## JWT API Access
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Separate from session auth. Users can configure JWT signing settings in `/settings/api-docs`. Used to authenticate external API consumers. Managed by `AuthJwtService`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Admin Access
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `requireAdminUser(request)` is used across all `/api/admin/*` routes. Admin users have a boolean flag in the users table set during bootstrap (`src/lib/db/bootstrap-admin.ts`).
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/runbooks/bug_tracker-local-dev.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: runbook
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [local-dev, setup, onboarding]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Local Development Setup
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Prerequisites
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Node.js (LTS)
[CLAUDE] - npm
[CLAUDE] - Docker + Docker Compose
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## First-Time Setup
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] # Clone the repo, then:
[CLAUDE] cp .env.example .env
[CLAUDE] npm install
[CLAUDE] docker compose up -d postgres
[CLAUDE] npm run db:migrate:postgres
[CLAUDE] npm run dev
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Open http://localhost:3000.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Daily Development Loop
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] docker compose up -d postgres   # ensure DB is running
[CLAUDE] npm run dev                     # starts Next.js dev server
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Running Tests
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] # Fast in-memory unit tests (no Docker needed)
[CLAUDE] npm run test
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # PostgreSQL-backed unit tests (requires running postgres container)
[CLAUDE] npm run test:unit:postgres
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # E2E tests (requires seeded test DB)
[CLAUDE] npm run test:e2e:seed
[CLAUDE] npm run test:e2e
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The default test command uses `BUG_TRACKER_TEST_DB_BACKEND=memory` which avoids the Docker dependency for fast local iteration.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Type Checking & Lint
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] npm run typecheck   # full TypeScript check (slow — clears .next first)
[CLAUDE] npm run lint        # ESLint
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## E2E Playwright Dev Server
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] For E2E test development, run the app on port 3001 with seeded data:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] npm run dev:playwright
[CLAUDE] # then in another terminal:
[CLAUDE] npm run test:e2e:ui
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Resetting the Database
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] No built-in reset script. To reset:
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] docker compose down -v            # removes postgres volume
[CLAUDE] docker compose up -d postgres
[CLAUDE] npm run db:migrate:postgres
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Troubleshooting
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **`predev` build:db-worker fails** — ensure `src/lib/db/postgres-worker.ts` has no TypeScript errors.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Database connection refused** — confirm `docker compose ps` shows postgres as healthy and `.env` `DATABASE_URL` points to `127.0.0.1:5432`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Test failures with postgres backend** — confirm postgres container is running and `npm run db:migrate:postgres` has been run recently.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/runbooks/bug_tracker-deploy.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: runbook
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [deployment, production, nginx]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Production Deployment
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Build & Start
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] npm run build   # Next.js production build + DB worker bundle
[CLAUDE] npm run start   # Start production server on port 3000
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The build step produces two artifacts:
[CLAUDE] - `.next/` — Next.js app
[CLAUDE] - `.next/db/postgres-worker.mjs` — standalone PostgreSQL worker thread
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Both must be present for the app to start correctly.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Environment
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Copy and configure `.env` for production:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] | Variable | Notes |
[CLAUDE] |---|---|
[CLAUDE] | `DATABASE_URL` | PostgreSQL connection string |
[CLAUDE] | `SESSION_SECRET` | Strong random secret (min 32 chars) |
[CLAUDE] | `SENDGRID_API_KEY` | Required for email delivery |
[CLAUDE] | `NEXT_PUBLIC_APP_URL` | Full public URL (used in email links) |
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Database Migrations
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Run migrations before starting the app after every release that changes the schema:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] npm run db:migrate:postgres
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Migrations are not applied automatically on startup.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Nginx Configuration
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] See `docs/deployment-nginx.md` for the full Nginx setup. The standard pattern:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```nginx
[CLAUDE] server {
[CLAUDE]     listen 443 ssl;
[CLAUDE]     server_name yourdomain.com;
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE]     location / {
[CLAUDE]         proxy_pass http://127.0.0.1:3000;
[CLAUDE]         proxy_set_header Host $host;
[CLAUDE]         proxy_set_header X-Real-IP $remote_addr;
[CLAUDE]     }
[CLAUDE] }
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Admin Bootstrap
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] On first deployment, bootstrap the admin user:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] # See src/lib/db/bootstrap-admin.ts for the mechanism
[CLAUDE] # Typically run once via a migration or startup script
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Checking Health
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Admin dashboard: `/admin/dashboard`
[CLAUDE] - Operational logs: `/admin/monitoring`
[CLAUDE] - `log/observability.ndjson` — structured log file for external ingestion
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/runbooks/bug_tracker-bug-data-import.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: runbook
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 4
[CLAUDE] tags: [import, export, data, admin]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Bug Data Import & Export
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Admin users can bulk-import bugs from CSV and export bugs to ZIP archives via the admin panel at `/admin/bug-data`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Import Flow
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] 1. **Upload CSV** — admin selects file in the bug data management panel
[CLAUDE] 2. **Validation** — system validates each row; reports invalid rows with field-level issues
[CLAUDE] 3. **Review** — admin sees validation summary: total / valid / invalid row counts; invalid rows listed with issues
[CLAUDE] 4. **Execute** — admin chooses duplicate strategy and confirms
[CLAUDE] 5. **Job tracking** — job status polled until `completed`, `completed_with_warnings`, or `failed`
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Duplicate Strategies
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] | Strategy | Behaviour |
[CLAUDE] |---|---|
[CLAUDE] | `skip_existing` | Skip any row where a matching bug already exists |
[CLAUDE] | `update_existing` | Overwrite fields on matching bugs |
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Import Summary Fields
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - `createdCount` — new bugs created
[CLAUDE] - `updatedCount` — existing bugs updated
[CLAUDE] - `skippedCount` — rows skipped (duplicate strategy)
[CLAUDE] - `failedCount` — rows that could not be processed
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Export Flow
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] 1. Admin triggers export from the bug data management panel
[CLAUDE] 2. Job is queued and runs asynchronously
[CLAUDE] 3. On completion, a download link is available (`downloadUrl` on the job record)
[CLAUDE] 4. Export manifest includes: bug count, history entry count, attachment count, missing file count
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Job Statuses
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] queued → running → completed
[CLAUDE]                  → completed_with_warnings
[CLAUDE]                  → failed
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Jobs are stored in `bug_data_jobs`. Running jobs show progress via `bugCount`, `attachmentCount`, and `historyEntryCount` in the summary.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Checking Job Issues
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Any errors or warnings on a job are accessible via the issue summary panel in the admin UI. The `getBugDataJobIssueMessages()` helper merges errors and warnings into a flat list.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-dual-database.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 5
[CLAUDE] tags: [database, testing, architecture]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-001: Dual Database Backend (PostgreSQL + In-Memory)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The app ships with two database backends selectable via `BUG_TRACKER_TEST_DB_BACKEND`:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - **`postgres`** — PostgreSQL via `pg` driver (production and postgres-specific tests)
[CLAUDE] - **`memory`** — in-process in-memory store (default for unit tests)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Rationale
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Running PostgreSQL for every unit test requires Docker and adds significant test startup time. An in-memory backend allows the fast test suite (`npm run test`) to run without any infrastructure.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Why:** Fast feedback loops during development. The in-memory backend provides sub-second test startup vs. waiting for Docker PostgreSQL to be ready.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **How to apply:** Default all unit tests to `memory` backend. Only use `npm run test:unit:postgres` when the change is specifically testing database-level behaviour (schema constraints, SQL queries, migrations).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Trade-offs
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] | | In-Memory | PostgreSQL |
[CLAUDE] |---|---|---|
[CLAUDE] | Speed | Very fast | Slower (network + process) |
[CLAUDE] | Fidelity | May miss SQL-specific behaviour | Matches production exactly |
[CLAUDE] | Infrastructure | None | Docker required |
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Implementation
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - `src/lib/db/database-client.ts` — abstraction interface
[CLAUDE] - `src/lib/db/local-test-database.ts` — in-memory implementation
[CLAUDE] - `src/lib/db/postgres-client.ts` — PostgreSQL implementation
[CLAUDE] - `src/lib/db/test-database.ts` — selects backend based on env var
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
