[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Organizations & Multi-Tenancy
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The app is multi-tenant. Every resource (bugs, projects, notifications) is scoped to an organization. The organization subsystem lives in `src/lib/organizations/`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Tenant Isolation
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The active organization for a session is tracked in `src/lib/organizations/active-organization-session.ts`. Every authenticated request resolves the active org via `requireActiveOrganizationSession()`, which throws `ActiveOrganizationSessionError` if no org is active. This is the tenancy boundary — all data queries include `organizationId`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `organization-switcher.tsx` in the sidebar allows users who belong to multiple orgs to switch context.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Membership & Access (`organization-membership-service.ts`, `organization-access-service.ts`)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Users join orgs via invitation or signup
[CLAUDE] - `requireOrganizationAdminAccessForUser` — gates org-admin operations
[CLAUDE] - `OrganizationAccessError` — thrown when access is denied
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Invitations (`organization-invitation-service.ts`)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Flow:
[CLAUDE] 1. Admin creates invitation → token stored in DB, email sent via `organization-invitation-email-service.ts`
[CLAUDE] 2. Invitee visits `/invitations/[invitationId]` → sees landing page
[CLAUDE] 3. Invitee accepts → `organization-invitation-activation-service.ts` creates membership
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Seat Management (`organization-seat-service.ts`)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Tracks the number of active seats per organization for billing purposes. Seat counts are checked before new members are added.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Billing (`organization-billing-service.ts`)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `src/lib/organizations/billing-ui.ts` provides UI helper logic for the billing page. The billing service interfaces with the subscription/plan layer. The billing page lives at `/billing`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Project Access Context
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `src/app/(authenticated)/project-access-context.ts` provides the "no project access" UI copy for users who are authenticated but not a member of any project in the active org.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Audit Log (`src/lib/audit/`)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `organization-audit-log-service.ts` records admin actions (user changes, project changes, settings changes) with actor, action, and target. The audit log is viewable at `/organization/audit`.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-tech-stack.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [next.js, postgresql, typescript, architecture]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-001: Technology Stack
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Context
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Bug Tracker needed a modern, full-stack TypeScript application with a relational database, email delivery, and support for both a browser app and API integrations (agent, extension, MCP).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decisions
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Next.js App Router (monorepo)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The entire application — UI, API routes, background scripts — lives in one Next.js project. This avoids a separate backend service, simplifies deployment, and keeps TypeScript types shared across the full stack.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Webpack mode is used explicitly (`next dev --webpack`, `next build --webpack`) rather than Turbopack, likely for stability with the custom worker bundle step.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### PostgreSQL as primary database
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] PostgreSQL was chosen over a managed BaaS (Supabase, PlanetScale, etc.) to allow full schema control, custom migrations, and on-premise deployment. The database client is abstracted behind `database-client.ts` so the backing store can be replaced.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Why not SQLite in production**: The worker-thread architecture (postgres-worker.ts bundled separately) suggests PostgreSQL-specific features (connection pooling, LISTEN/NOTIFY potential) were important.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### In-memory SQLite for tests
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Running `npm test` uses an in-memory SQLite backend to avoid requiring Docker for the default test suite. PostgreSQL-backed tests are opt-in via `npm run test:unit:postgres`. This is a deliberate DX tradeoff: fast tests by default, real-DB tests when needed.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### SendGrid for email
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Email delivery is handled by SendGrid with plain HTML templates. No React Email, MJML, or other template framework — templates are `.html` files with string interpolation. Simple and dependency-free.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### No Zod at API boundaries
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Request body validation uses plain TypeScript `typeof` guards rather than Zod schemas. This is consistent throughout all route handlers. This reduces bundle size and keeps validation logic explicit, at the cost of more verbose validation code.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### shadcn/ui + Tailwind CSS 4
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] UI components use shadcn/ui (component source in `src/components/ui/`). Tailwind CSS 4 with PostCSS provides utility styling. This avoids a heavy component library runtime while keeping design consistent.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### MCP Server for LLM integration
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk` is included as a production dependency, exposing bug tracker operations as MCP tools. This positions the product for LLM-driven agentic workflows without requiring a separate microservice.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Status
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Active — reflects the current codebase as of April 2026.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-database-worker.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 2
[CLAUDE] tags: [postgresql, worker-thread, esbuild, architecture]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-002: PostgreSQL Worker Thread Architecture
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Context
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Next.js API routes run in a serverless-style execution environment. Long-lived PostgreSQL connection pools do not work well across cold-starts and the Next.js module lifecycle.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Database operations that need a persistent connection pool run in a dedicated Node.js worker thread (`src/lib/db/postgres-worker.ts`). The worker is compiled separately by esbuild into `.next/db/postgres-worker.mjs` and loaded at runtime.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] This is why `package.json` has two build steps:
[CLAUDE] 1. `next build` — compiles the Next.js app
[CLAUDE] 2. `build:db-worker` — bundles the worker with esbuild (`--platform=node --format=esm --packages=external`)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The `predev` hook ensures the worker bundle exists before `next dev` starts.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Tradeoffs
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Pro**: Connection pool lifecycle is independent of the Next.js request handler lifecycle. The worker persists between requests.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Con**: Additional build step. Worker must be rebuilt when `postgres-worker.ts` changes. Adds complexity to the test setup (`local-test-database-runtime.ts` handles this for tests).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Status
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Active.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-dual-db-testing.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 2
[CLAUDE] tags: [testing, sqlite, postgresql, test-strategy]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-003: Dual Database Backend for Testing
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Context
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Integration tests that require a live PostgreSQL instance are slow to set up in CI and locally. But pure mocks would hide real SQL bugs.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The database client is abstracted. Two backends are implemented:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - `memory` (SQLite in-process) — default for `npm test` and `npm run test:unit`
[CLAUDE] - `postgres` — used by `npm run test:unit:postgres` and E2E tests
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Selection is via `BUG_TRACKER_TEST_DB_BACKEND` environment variable.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `postgres-test-reset.ts` truncates all tables between tests when running in postgres mode, ensuring test isolation without recreating the schema.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Rationale
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - `npm test` runs without Docker — zero-friction for all contributors
[CLAUDE] - `npm run test:unit:postgres` catches DB-specific bugs (e.g., constraint violations, query planner differences) when explicitly opted into
[CLAUDE] - E2E tests (`npm run test:e2e`) always use PostgreSQL because they test the full stack
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Status
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Active.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
