[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Deployment
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Production Build
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] # Build Next.js app + DB worker bundle
[CLAUDE] npm run build
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Start production server
[CLAUDE] npm run start
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The build step runs two commands:
[CLAUDE] 1. `next build --webpack` — compiles the Next.js application
[CLAUDE] 2. `build:db-worker` — bundles `postgres-worker.ts` into `.next/db/postgres-worker.mjs` via esbuild
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Both must succeed before starting the production server.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Environment
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Set all required environment variables before starting. At minimum:
[CLAUDE] - PostgreSQL connection details
[CLAUDE] - Session secret / cookie config
[CLAUDE] - SendGrid credentials (if email is required in production)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Database Migrations
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Run migrations before starting the new app version:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] npm run db:migrate:postgres
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] This uses `node --env-file=.env` so the `.env` file must be present and contain valid PostgreSQL credentials.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Nginx Reverse Proxy
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] See `docs/deployment-nginx.md` in the repository for:
[CLAUDE] - Domain-based access configuration
[CLAUDE] - SSL termination
[CLAUDE] - Proxy pass to `localhost:3000`
[CLAUDE] - Static asset caching headers
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## CI Pipeline
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] # Full local CI (lint + typecheck + tests + build)
[CLAUDE] npm run ci
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Quick CI (skip E2E)
[CLAUDE] npm run ci:quick
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # With E2E
[CLAUDE] npm run ci:e2e
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Scripts are in `scripts/local-ci.sh`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## AWS EC2 Deployment
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] See `tasks/prd-aws-ec2-deployment.md` for the planned EC2 deployment specification.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Observability in Production
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Structured logs are written to `log/observability.ndjson`. See `docs/observability.md` for log rotation, alerting integration, and monitoring setup.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## run.sh
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `run.sh` in the repo root is a convenience script for starting the application in a server environment. Review before use in production to confirm it matches your deployment target.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
