[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/concepts/bug_tracker-observability-model.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: concept
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 4
[CLAUDE] tags: [observability, logging, alerts, performance, monitoring]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Observability Model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The observability model distinguishes three levels of operational data:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## 1. Operational Logs
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Every HTTP request produces a log entry via `withRequestObservability`. Entries record: method, path, status code, duration, and any error details.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Sensitive fields are redacted before storage (via `observability-redaction.ts`) — passwords, tokens, and other configured field names are stripped from logged request bodies.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Logs are dual-written:
[CLAUDE] - **Database** (`operational_logs` table) — queryable by admins via `GET /api/admin/logs`
[CLAUDE] - **File** (`log/observability.ndjson`) — newline-delimited JSON for external log aggregators
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Severity scale: `debug < info < warn < error < critical`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## 2. Error Groups
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Errors with stack traces are fingerprinted and grouped. A fingerprint is a stable identifier derived from the normalised stack trace + error message. Grouping prevents the admin error view from being flooded with identical errors.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Each group tracks: occurrence count, first/last seen, representative stack trace, and optionally a linked bug.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## 3. Operational Alerts
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Alerts are higher-signal than log entries. They represent conditions requiring human attention. Unlike log entries (append-only), alerts have a mutable status: `open → acknowledged → resolved`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Alerts include a severity (`info | warn | error | critical`) and a source tag. Admins can create bugs directly from alerts, creating a traceable link from operational signal to tracked work item.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Client-Side Observability
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Page load timing from the browser is posted to `POST /api/observability/page-load` and stored alongside server-side events. This gives end-to-end visibility: server request time + client render time.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Performance Metrics
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Endpoint performance is derived from the operational log — no separate APM agent. `getEndpointPerformance(window)` computes p50/p95/p99 from stored log entries within the time window. This means metrics are only as granular as the log retention period.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Limitations
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Log retention is database-limited — no built-in rotation or archival policy
[CLAUDE] - Performance percentiles are computed at query time (no pre-aggregation) — may be slow on high-traffic instances with large log tables
[CLAUDE] - No distributed tracing (no trace IDs across service calls)
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ---
