[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Database
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Backends
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The app supports two database backends, selected via the `BUG_TRACKER_TEST_DB_BACKEND` environment variable:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] | Backend | When used |
[CLAUDE] |---|---|
[CLAUDE] | PostgreSQL | Production and `test:unit:postgres` suite |
[CLAUDE] | In-memory | Default test suite (`npm run test`) |
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `src/lib/db/database-client.ts` abstracts the backend. `src/lib/db/index.ts` exports `getDatabase()`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## PostgreSQL Setup
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Config: `postgres-config.ts` reads `DATABASE_URL` or individual `POSTGRES_*` env vars from `.env`.
[CLAUDE] - Client: `postgres-client.ts` wraps the `pg` npm package.
[CLAUDE] - Schema DDL: `postgres-schema.ts`; test helpers in `postgres-schema.test.ts`.
[CLAUDE] - Migrations: applied via `npm run db:migrate:postgres` (runs `scripts/migrate-postgres.ts`).
[CLAUDE] - Bootstrap: `postgres-bootstrap.ts` handles first-run setup; `bootstrap-admin.ts` seeds the initial admin account.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## PostgreSQL Worker
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Certain heavy operations run in a separate worker thread to avoid blocking the Next.js server:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Worker source: `src/lib/db/postgres-worker.ts`
[CLAUDE] - Built to: `.next/db/postgres-worker.mjs` via esbuild
[CLAUDE] - Bootstrap script: `postgres-worker-bootstrap.mjs`
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The worker is built automatically before `dev` and `build` scripts via the `predev` npm hook.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Schema
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Core tables (inferred from services and stores):
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] | Table | Key fields |
[CLAUDE] |---|---|
[CLAUDE] | `users` | id, name, email, password_hash, role, is_verified |
[CLAUDE] | `sessions` | token, user_id, expires_at |
[CLAUDE] | `auth_action_tokens` | token, type, user_id, expires_at |
[CLAUDE] | `organizations` | id, name, slug, billing_plan |
[CLAUDE] | `organization_members` | org_id, user_id, role |
[CLAUDE] | `organization_invitations` | token, org_id, email, status |
[CLAUDE] | `projects` | id, org_id, name, key, is_archived |
[CLAUDE] | `project_sections` | id, project_id, name, display_order |
[CLAUDE] | `bugs` | id, org_id, project_id, section_id, title, description, severity, status, reporter_user_id, assignee_user_id, is_archived |
[CLAUDE] | `bug_comments` | id, bug_id, user_id, body, visibility |
[CLAUDE] | `bug_attachments` | id, bug_id, file_path, file_name |
[CLAUDE] | `bug_history` | id, bug_id, event_type, changed_fields (json), created_by |
[CLAUDE] | `bug_data_jobs` | id, org_id, job_type, status, summary (json) |
[CLAUDE] | `operational_logs` | id, severity, message, context (json), fingerprint |
[CLAUDE] | `operational_alerts` | id, severity, status, source, grouping_key |
[CLAUDE] | `notifications` | id, event_type, recipient_id, delivery_status |
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Full canonical schema: `src/lib/db/schema.ts` and `postgres-schema.ts`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Local Docker Setup
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] docker compose up -d postgres   # starts postgres on 127.0.0.1:5432
[CLAUDE] npm run db:migrate:postgres     # applies migrations
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Credentials default to values in `.env.example`.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-tech-stack.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [nextjs, react, typescript, postgresql]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-001: Technology Stack
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Build Bug Tracker as a **Next.js 16 monolith** (App Router) with TypeScript, React 19, PostgreSQL, and SendGrid.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Context
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The project needed a full-stack TypeScript application that could ship both the authenticated web UI and the REST API from a single codebase with minimal operational overhead.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Rationale
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Why:** Next.js App Router collocates API Route Handlers with UI pages, eliminating a separate API service and reducing deployment surface. TypeScript throughout enables shared types between client UI, API routes, and service layer with no duplication.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Why PostgreSQL:** Relational data model (orgs → projects → bugs → comments/history) maps naturally to SQL. The in-memory test backend (swapped via `BUG_TRACKER_TEST_DB_BACKEND=memory`) allows fast unit tests without Docker.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Why SendGrid:** Transactional email with template management; optional for local dev (variables left empty).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **How to apply:** Avoid adding a separate Express/Fastify API server. New backend logic belongs in `src/lib/*` service/store files, surfaced via Next.js Route Handlers.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-dual-database.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 4
[CLAUDE] tags: [database, testing, postgresql, in-memory]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-002: Dual Database Backend (PostgreSQL + In-Memory)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The `getDatabase()` factory selects between a PostgreSQL client and an in-memory implementation based on `BUG_TRACKER_TEST_DB_BACKEND`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Context
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Running full PostgreSQL for every unit test would require Docker and incur significant test startup time.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Why:** An in-memory backend allows `npm run test` to run quickly without infrastructure. PostgreSQL-specific tests (`npm run test:unit:postgres`) are run separately only when database behaviour matters.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Why not mock:** Using a real interface (same `DatabaseClient` type) rather than mocks means tests exercise actual query logic. The tradeoff is that in-memory tests may miss PostgreSQL-specific edge cases — covered by the separate postgres suite.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **How to apply:** Default new tests to the memory backend. Only reach for `test:unit:postgres` when the test specifically exercises SQL syntax, transactions, constraints, or migrations.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-observability-wrapper.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [observability, middleware, api]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-003: withRequestObservability Wrapper on All Routes
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Every exported route handler is wrapped: `export const GET = withRequestObservability("GET", GETHandler)`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Why:** Consistent timing, error capture, and structured logging across all API routes without requiring each handler to remember to call observability hooks. A handler that throws unexpectedly is still recorded.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Why not middleware:** Next.js middleware runs on the edge and lacks access to the full Node.js runtime (filesystem, pg client). The wrapper pattern runs in the Node.js runtime alongside the handler.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **How to apply:** When adding a new Route Handler, always export via `withRequestObservability`. Never export the raw handler function directly.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/concepts/bug_tracker-domain-model.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: concept
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 5
[CLAUDE] tags: [domain, data-model, entities]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Domain Model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Entity Hierarchy
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] Organization
[CLAUDE] ├── has many Members (Users with roles)
[CLAUDE] ├── has many Projects
[CLAUDE] │   └── has many Sections
[CLAUDE] │       └── has many Bugs
[CLAUDE] │           ├── has many Comments
[CLAUDE] │           ├── has many Attachments
[CLAUDE] │           └── has many History Entries
[CLAUDE] ├── has many Invitations
[CLAUDE] ├── has one Billing plan
[CLAUDE] └── has many Audit Log entries
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Key Entities
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Bug
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The central entity. Fields: title, description, severity, status, projectId, sectionId, reporterUserId, assigneeUserId, isArchived.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Severity and status are string-typed enums enforced by service-layer validation, not DB constraints.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Organization
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Top-level tenant boundary. All bug data is scoped to an org. Users switch orgs via the org switcher; the active org is stored in the session.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Project / Section
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Projects group bugs by product area. Sections provide ordering within a project (analogous to columns in a kanban board).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Bug History Entry
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Immutable audit trail. Each entry records `eventType` and a list of `changedFields` with `previousValue` / `nextValue`. Source is classified as user, import, or system.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Testing Session
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Represents an active QA session. While a testing session is open, the Chrome extension can attach evidence (screenshots, recordings) to bugs through the extension evidence API.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Operational Alert
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] A monitored-infrastructure concern (distinct from bugs). Alerts have a `groupingKey` for deduplication and can be promoted to bugs via the admin panel.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Status Lifecycle
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] New → Triaged → In Progress → Ready for QA → Closed
[CLAUDE]                                                 ↑
[CLAUDE]                                           (can reopen)
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `isArchived` is orthogonal to status — a bug can be archived at any status.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/concepts/bug_tracker-agent-model.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: concept
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [agent, automation, ai, mcp]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Agent Integration Model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## What "Agent" Means Here
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] An agent is an automated process (AI or script) that interacts with bugs programmatically. Agents authenticate via API key rather than user session and operate through the `/api/agent/*` REST API or the MCP tool server.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Claim / Work Model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Agents use a claim-based workflow:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] 1. `GET /api/agent/bugs` — fetch claimable bugs
[CLAUDE] 2. `POST /api/agent/bugs/:id/claim` — claim with `claimedBy` identifier (agent name/ID)
[CLAUDE] 3. `PATCH /api/agent/bugs/:id/status` — update work state and optional `statusNote` as the agent progresses
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] This prevents two agents from working on the same bug simultaneously.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## MCP Server
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `mcp-server.ts` exposes bug operations as structured tools consumable by LLMs via the Model Context Protocol (`@modelcontextprotocol/sdk`). Invoked via `npm run mcp:server`. This allows an LLM to list, read, and update bugs as tool calls within an agent loop.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Ralph Agent
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The `scripts/ralph/` directory contains a specialised internal agent with:
[CLAUDE] - `project-context.md` — project knowledge injected into the agent's context
[CLAUDE] - `prompt.md` — system instructions for Ralph's behaviour
[CLAUDE] - `ralph.sh` — shell runner that launches the agent process
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Ralph appears to be a QA/intake agent operating on the bug tracker's own bugs.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Recommended Multi-Agent Design (from product notes)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The raw sources describe a preferred architecture of specialised agents rather than one monolithic agent:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] | Agent | Responsibility |
[CLAUDE] |---|---|
[CLAUDE] | Intake | Cleans and structures incoming reports |
[CLAUDE] | Triage | Prioritises and routes bugs |
[CLAUDE] | Investigation | Correlates logs, releases, stack traces |
[CLAUDE] | QA | Suggests verification test scenarios |
[CLAUDE] | Release | Assesses whether bug fixes are safe to ship |
[CLAUDE] | Support | Produces customer-facing summaries |
[CLAUDE] | Insights | Identifies recurring patterns |
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/runbooks/bug_tracker-local-setup.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: runbook
