[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/tech-debt/bug_tracker-route-handler-pattern.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: tech-debt
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 2
[CLAUDE] tags: [api, routes, consistency]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Inconsistent Route Handler Observability Wrapping
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Issue
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Most Route Handlers follow the pattern:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```ts
[CLAUDE] async function GETHandler(request: NextRequest) { ... }
[CLAUDE] export const GET = withRequestObservability("GET", GETHandler);
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] However, `src/app/api/bugs/[bugId]/history/route.ts` exports the handler directly:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```ts
[CLAUDE] export async function GET(request: NextRequest, context: RouteContext) { ... }
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] This means the bug history endpoint is not covered by request observability — its timing, errors, and access patterns are not recorded in operational logs.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Risk
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Low functional risk, but monitoring blind spot. A slow or erroring history endpoint will not appear in the admin performance dashboard.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Fix
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Refactor `history/route.ts` to use `withRequestObservability` consistent with all other routes.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
