[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-tech-stack.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [nextjs, typescript, react, tech-stack]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-001: Tech Stack Selection
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Use Next.js 16 (App Router) with TypeScript, React 19, Tailwind CSS 4, and PostgreSQL.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Context
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The application needs:
[CLAUDE] - Authenticated multi-tenant workspace (server-rendered pages + API routes)
[CLAUDE] - A single deployable unit covering both UI and backend API
[CLAUDE] - Strong typing for correctness across a complex domain model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Choices Made
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Next.js App Router
[CLAUDE] Full-stack in one repo. API routes and React Server Components coexist. Reduces infra complexity for a team-sized product.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Webpack mode** (`--webpack`) used explicitly — `next dev --webpack` and `next build --webpack`. The default Turbopack is not used, likely for plugin compatibility.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### PostgreSQL over SQLite/NoSQL
[CLAUDE] Relational model fits the domain (orgs → projects → bugs → comments/attachments/history). PostgreSQL enables complex queries for monitoring, grouping, and audit.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### In-Memory DB for Tests
[CLAUDE] `BUG_TRACKER_TEST_DB_BACKEND=memory` lets the default test suite run without Docker. PostgreSQL tests are opt-in via `npm run test:unit:postgres`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### shadcn/ui + Tailwind CSS 4
[CLAUDE] Component primitives from shadcn with Radix UI under the hood. Tailwind 4 for styling.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### Zod 4 for Validation
[CLAUDE] Used for schema validation at API boundaries and form inputs.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ### SendGrid for Email
[CLAUDE] Transactional email via SendGrid. Configurable via env vars; disabled locally when key is absent.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-database-worker.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 2
[CLAUDE] tags: [database, worker-thread, postgresql, build]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-002: PostgreSQL Worker Thread Pattern
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Run PostgreSQL client operations in a Node.js worker thread via `postgres-worker.ts`, bundled separately to `.next/db/postgres-worker.mjs`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Context
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Next.js edge runtime and certain Next.js compilation contexts cannot use native Node.js modules like `pg` directly. Running the PG client in a worker thread isolates it from the main Next.js runtime.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Build Step
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```bash
[CLAUDE] esbuild src/lib/db/postgres-worker.ts \
[CLAUDE]   --bundle --platform=node --format=esm \
[CLAUDE]   --packages=external \
[CLAUDE]   --outfile=.next/db/postgres-worker.mjs
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] This runs as a `predev` hook (before `next dev`) and as part of `npm run build`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Tradeoffs
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Pro:** Avoids native module compatibility issues with Next.js bundler.  
[CLAUDE] **Con:** Requires an extra build step; worker must be rebuilt when worker source changes.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Worker Bootstrap
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `postgres-worker-bootstrap.mjs` — initialisation logic run inside the worker.  
[CLAUDE] `postgres-bootstrap.ts` — schema bootstrap on first run.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-agent-api-design.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [agent, api, mcp, automation]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR-003: Separate Agent API Surface
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Provide a dedicated `/api/agent/` route group for automated agents, separate from the browser-session API.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Context
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Automated agents (CI bots, LLM agents, external integrations) need to operate on bugs programmatically. Mixing this with the browser session API would complicate auth and response formats.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Design
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Agent auth via `requireAgentApiUser()` — token-based, no cookie dependency
[CLAUDE] - Responses via `createAgentApiSuccessResponse()` / `createAgentApiErrorResponse()` — consistent machine-readable envelope
[CLAUDE] - Scoped operations: list claimable bugs, claim a bug, update agent work state
[CLAUDE] - MCP server (`npm run mcp:server`) exposes operations as tools for LLM agents via `@modelcontextprotocol/sdk`
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Claim Model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Agents explicitly claim a bug (`POST /api/agent/bugs/[id]/claim`) with a `claimedBy` identifier before updating it. This prevents two agents from working the same bug concurrently.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Future Direction
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Product roadmap calls for specialised agents (intake, triage, investigation, QA, release, support). The current agent API is the foundation for this multi-agent coordination layer.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/concepts/bug_tracker-domain-model.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: concept
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 5
[CLAUDE] tags: [domain, model, bugs, organizations, projects]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Domain Model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Entity Hierarchy
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] User
[CLAUDE] └── belongs to one or more Organizations (via Membership)
[CLAUDE]     └── Organization
[CLAUDE]         ├── has many Projects
[CLAUDE]         │   ├── has many Sections
[CLAUDE]         │   └── has many Bugs (scoped to project + section)
[CLAUDE]         │       ├── has many Comments
[CLAUDE]         │       ├── has many Attachments
[CLAUDE]         │       ├── has many HistoryEntries
[CLAUDE]         │       └── has TestingSessions (QA evidence)
[CLAUDE]         ├── has AuditLog
[CLAUDE]         ├── has NotificationSettings
[CLAUDE]         └── has Billing state
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Bug Fields
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] | Field | Type | Notes |
[CLAUDE] |---|---|---|
[CLAUDE] | `title` | string | Required |
[CLAUDE] | `description` | string | Required |
[CLAUDE] | `severity` | string | e.g. critical, high, medium, low |
[CLAUDE] | `status` | enum | New, Triaged, In Progress, Ready for QA, Closed |
[CLAUDE] | `reporterUserId` | number? | Who filed it |
[CLAUDE] | `assigneeUserId` | number? | Who owns it |
[CLAUDE] | `projectId` | number | Required |
[CLAUDE] | `sectionId` | number | Required |
[CLAUDE] | `is_archived` | boolean | Soft-delete |
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Organization Membership Roles
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Roles control access to admin surfaces and project membership. `requireOrganizationAdminAccessForUser()` gates admin-only operations.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Active Organization Session
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] A user can belong to multiple organizations. The "active" org is stored in session state. All bug/project queries are scoped to the active org.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Project Sections
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Projects have ordered sections (like columns in a board or phases in a pipeline). Sections have `displayOrder` and `isArchived`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Operational Alerts vs Bugs
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] **Operational Alerts** come from the monitoring system (log-derived, auto-detected).  
[CLAUDE] **Bugs** are human or agent-submitted issue reports.  
[CLAUDE] Alerts can be promoted to bugs via `createBugFromOperationalAlert()`.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/concepts/bug_tracker-agent-architecture.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: concept
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 2
[CLAUDE] tags: [agent, automation, multi-agent, mcp, ai]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Agent Architecture Concept
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The product roadmap (from `shared/agent_bugtracker.md`) describes an agent layer that goes well beyond a simple API wrapper.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Specialised Agent Roles
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Rather than one generic agent, the design calls for a set of focused agents:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] | Agent | Responsibility |
[CLAUDE] |---|---|
[CLAUDE] | **Intake** | Structures messy bug reports, rewrites vague titles, extracts reproduction steps, classifies severity |
[CLAUDE] | **Triage** | Ranks business impact, routes to team, flags blockers, recommends escalation |
[CLAUDE] | **Investigation** | Correlates logs, recent commits, releases, feature flags, and past similar bugs |
[CLAUDE] | **QA** | Suggests test scenarios, verification steps, regression scope |
[CLAUDE] | **Release** | Checks whether a fix is safe to ship |
[CLAUDE] | **Support** | Generates customer-safe summaries and workaround notes |
[CLAUDE] | **Insights** | Finds recurring patterns, modules with regressions, systemic quality issues |
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Agent Coordination
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Agents should coordinate with each other on shared bugs. The `agent-integration.ts` and claim model (via `/api/agent/bugs/[id]/claim`) provide the primitives for preventing duplicate work.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## MCP Integration
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `mcp-server.ts` exposes bug tracker operations as MCP tools. This allows Claude and other LLM agents to interact with the bug tracker natively within their tool-calling loop.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Confidence-Based Automation
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Rather than silent automation, the design recommends surfacing confidence scores:
[CLAUDE] - `likely duplicate: 91%`
[CLAUDE] - `likely module: billing service, 84%`
[CLAUDE] - `likely caused by latest release, 73%`
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] This builds user trust and allows human override before high-confidence actions are taken autonomously.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Triage Modes
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - **Conservative** — agent suggests only, human approves
[CLAUDE] - **Assisted** — agent auto-fills fields, human approves
[CLAUDE] - **Autonomous** — low-risk bugs triaged without human involvement
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Evidence Correlation
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Investigation agents should pull in: logs, API failures, session recordings, deployment history, recent releases, feature flags, analytics anomalies, test failures. Current infrastructure (observability logs, operational alerts, bug history) provides the data substrate for this.
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
