[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-tech-stack.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [nextjs, typescript, postgresql, react]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR: Technology Stack
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Build the bug tracker as a **Next.js 16 full-stack application** using the App Router, TypeScript, React 19, PostgreSQL, and Tailwind CSS.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Why
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Next.js App Router colocates API routes and UI in one repo, reducing operational complexity for a team-sized product.
[CLAUDE] - TypeScript throughout enables shared types between API route handlers and client components without a separate schema layer.
[CLAUDE] - PostgreSQL provides relational integrity needed for multi-tenant data (orgs → projects → bugs → history).
[CLAUDE] - Tailwind CSS + shadcn/ui (Radix primitives) gives a component library without a large design-system dependency.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Consequences
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - **Webpack mode** is explicitly forced (`--webpack` in dev and build scripts), suggesting Turbopack was evaluated and had issues.
[CLAUDE] - The MCP SDK dependency (`@modelcontextprotocol/sdk`) ties the project to LLM tooling from the start.
[CLAUDE] - No ORM is used — all DB access is raw SQL via `pg`, keeping query control but requiring manual schema management.
[CLAUDE] - Dual-database testing (in-memory vs PostgreSQL) adds complexity but enables fast unit test feedback loops.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-dual-database-testing.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 3
[CLAUDE] tags: [testing, database, in-memory, postgresql]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR: Dual Database Testing Strategy
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Maintain **two database backends**: an in-memory adapter (default for unit tests) and PostgreSQL (for integration/postgres-specific tests).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Controlled by environment variable: `BUG_TRACKER_TEST_DB_BACKEND=memory|postgres`
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Why
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Fast unit test feedback: the in-memory backend runs tests without requiring Docker or a live PostgreSQL instance. Developers can run `npm run test` immediately after checkout.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] PostgreSQL-specific behavior (constraints, transactions, advanced queries) is tested separately with `npm run test:unit:postgres`, which requires the Docker service to be running.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## How to Apply
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Default `npm run test` → in-memory, fast, no Docker needed
[CLAUDE] - `npm run test:unit:postgres` → real PostgreSQL, use when changing DB schema, queries, or migration scripts
[CLAUDE] - E2E tests (`npm run test:e2e`) always use PostgreSQL via Docker
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Consequences
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Risk of in-memory/PostgreSQL behavioral divergence — mitigated by running postgres tests in CI.
[CLAUDE] - `database-client.ts` must maintain compatible interfaces across both adapters.
[CLAUDE] - Test isolation: `postgres-test-reset.ts` truncates tables; in-memory resets on process.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/decisions/bug_tracker-agent-api-design.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: decision
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 2
[CLAUDE] tags: [agent, api, mcp, cli]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # ADR: Agent API Design (Three-Interface Approach)
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Decision
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Expose agent functionality through **three parallel interfaces**: a REST API (`/api/agent/`), a CLI (`npm run bugs:cli`), and an MCP server (`npm run mcp:server`).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Why
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - **REST API** allows any HTTP client (including LLM-based agents) to interact without a local binary.
[CLAUDE] - **CLI** enables scripted local workflows and testing agent logic without an HTTP server.
[CLAUDE] - **MCP Server** integrates with LLM tooling that speaks the Model Context Protocol natively, enabling tool-use by Claude and other models.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] The claim-before-work pattern (`POST /api/agent/bugs/[bugId]/claim`) prevents multiple agents from picking up the same bug without a distributed lock.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Consequences
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] - Three entry points to keep in sync when bug operations change.
[CLAUDE] - The `agent-api.ts` helper module centralizes auth, error mapping, and response shaping so the three interfaces share common behavior.
[CLAUDE] - Multi-agent coordination remains partially unresolved — see [open question](../open-questions/bug_tracker-agent-coordination.md).
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/concepts/bug_tracker-domain-model.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: concept
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 5
[CLAUDE] tags: [domain, data-model, bugs, organizations, projects]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Domain Model
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Core Entities
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] Organization
[CLAUDE]     │
[CLAUDE]     ├── Members (Users with roles)
[CLAUDE]     ├── Projects
[CLAUDE]     │       └── Sections
[CLAUDE]     │               └── Bugs
[CLAUDE]     │                     ├── Comments
[CLAUDE]     │                     ├── Attachments
[CLAUDE]     │                     └── History entries
[CLAUDE]     │
[CLAUDE]     ├── Invitations
[CLAUDE]     └── Notification Settings
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Bug
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Central entity. Key fields:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] | Field | Type | Notes |
[CLAUDE] |---|---|---|
[CLAUDE] | `title` | string | Required |
[CLAUDE] | `description` | string | Required |
[CLAUDE] | `severity` | enum | e.g. `low`, `medium`, `high`, `critical` |
[CLAUDE] | `status` | enum | `New`, `Triaged`, `In Progress`, `Ready for QA`, `Closed` |
[CLAUDE] | `projectId` | FK | Required |
[CLAUDE] | `sectionId` | FK | Required |
[CLAUDE] | `reporterUserId` | FK | Optional |
[CLAUDE] | `assigneeUserId` | FK | Optional |
[CLAUDE] | `is_archived` | boolean | Soft archive |
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Agent-specific fields: `claimedBy` (string agent name), agent `state`, `statusNote`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Organization
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Top-level tenant. Has a `slug` (URL-friendly identifier), `name`, billing state, and seat count.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Project
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Belongs to an organization. Has a `key` (short code), `name`, `description`, and `isArchived` flag. Contains ordered **sections**.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## User
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Global (not org-scoped). Users join organizations via membership records. Roles are per-membership. QA users are a distinct user type managed by admins.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Testing Session
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] A structured QA session tied to a user. Evidence uploads via the Chrome extension require an active testing session. Logs are recorded per session in `testing_session_logs`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Operational Alert
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] A system-generated alert (not a user-filed bug). Admins can acknowledge/resolve alerts or promote them to bugs via `POST /api/admin/alerts/[id]/bugs`.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === FILE: wiki/concepts/bug_tracker-request-lifecycle.md ===
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] type: concept
[CLAUDE] owner: engineering
[CLAUDE] last_updated: 2026-04-20
[CLAUDE] source_count: 4
[CLAUDE] tags: [api, observability, auth, request-lifecycle]
[CLAUDE] status: active
[CLAUDE] ---
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] # Request Lifecycle
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Every API request flows through the same chain:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 1. Next.js routes request to handler
[CLAUDE] 2. withRequestObservability wraps handler
[CLAUDE] 3. Handler validates request body / params
[CLAUDE] 4. Auth guard called (requireAuthenticatedUser / requireAdminUser / requireAgentApiUser)
[CLAUDE] 5. Active organization resolved (requireActiveOrganizationSession) if needed
[CLAUDE] 6. Service function called
[CLAUDE] 7. Response returned
[CLAUDE] 8. withRequestObservability records method, path, status, duration to operational_logs
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Observability Wrapper
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] `withRequestObservability(method, handler)` in `src/lib/monitoring/request-observability.ts`:
[CLAUDE] - Wraps every exported handler
[CLAUDE] - Catches unhandled errors and records them with fingerprints
[CLAUDE] - Does not suppress errors — re-throws after logging
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Error Handling Pattern
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] API routes follow a consistent try/catch pattern:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```typescript
[CLAUDE] try {
[CLAUDE]   // business logic
[CLAUDE] } catch (error) {
[CLAUDE]   if (error instanceof AuthenticationError) return 401
[CLAUDE]   if (error instanceof SomeServiceError) return 400 / 404 / 409
[CLAUDE]   throw error  // unexpected — let observability catch it
[CLAUDE] }
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] Service-specific error classes (`BugServiceError`, `ProjectServiceError`, etc.) carry typed codes that handlers map to HTTP status codes.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ## Request Validation
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] No schema library (e.g. Zod) is used in API routes. Validation is done via explicit type guard conditions on the parsed JSON body:
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] ```typescript
[CLAUDE] if (!body || typeof body.name !== "string") {
[CLAUDE]   return NextResponse.json({ error: "..." }, { status: 400 })
[CLAUDE] }
[CLAUDE] ```
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] This pattern is consistent across all routes.
[CLAUDE] 
[CLAUDE] === END FILE ===
[CLAUDE] 
